==== CRP and ESR: Diagnostically Informative Normal Findings

C-reactive protein (CRP) and erythrocyte sedimentation rate (ESR) are typically *normal* in ME/CFS despite significant symptom burden. This normal finding is itself diagnostically important: it distinguishes ME/CFS from active inflammatory conditions such as rheumatoid arthritis, systemic lupus erythematosus, and active infection, all of which produce CRP and ESR elevation. Clinicians frequently misinterpret normal CRP as evidence against organic disease; in ME/CFS, normal CRP is part of the expected biomarker profile rather than a disconfirmatory finding

